          <h2>Projects</h2>
          <p>I believe the best designed and built projects use the simplest solutions. They're easily scaled or extended by any developer, and need minimal maintenance year after year. Here are a few of my projects that I think meet that criteria. Please <a href="#email-contact-form" class="email-contact-button">contact me</a> for more examples, or additional information on any project listed here.</p>
          <hr>
          <h5>Personal website and blog at <a href="http://www.followrhythm.com">www.FollowRhythm.com</a></h5>
          <p>This is a website built with Ruby on Rails, using RefineryCMS. The design is based on a Bootstrap template from Creative Tim. It includes an integration with a custom email API and Google Maps where a boat's position is displayed in real time. Emails are sent periodically from a satellite phone containing current Latitude and Longitude information. The API parses the emails and saves the position reports to the database. The front end uses the data to plot the boat's current position and route on a <a href="http://www.followrhythm.com/find-us">map</a>.</p>
          <hr>
          <h5>Enterprise Blogging Platform For G5</h5>
          <p>Working for G5, I designed and built a blogging platform that's currently hosting over 800 blogs. A Ruby on Rails application provides a Bootstrap UI for creating, editing, and publishing blogs. It also provides an API to deploy the blog as a set of static pages or serve them up via AJAX requests. On the front end, javascript/jQuery takes care of the viewing, navigation and filtering for end users.</p>
          <hr>
          <h5>Heroku Platform API Integration for G5</h5>
          <p>Again for G5, I built an internal tool (Dubbed The App Wrangler) for managing several hundred applications hosted on Heroku. A Ruby on Rails app works with the Heroku Platform API to help identify apps with excessive hosting costs and manage configurations.</p>
          <hr>
          <h5>Social Media Proxy Service for G5</h5>
          <p>For G5 I built a service that delivers social media feeds from Facebook, Twitter, Instagram and others to thousands of client websites. Using Ruby, it provides an adapter that interacts with each service's API, and provides it's own API that delivers content to customer websites. API quotas are carefully managed by cacheing fresh data in Redis when API usage is within acceptable limits. When we're approaching an API limit, data is served from memory. On the front end, session storage is used to help alleviate the load on our own servers.</p>
          <hr>
          <h5>Automated Testing for G5</h5>
          <p>Using Ruby, Selenium and Pusher, I built a tool to automate a tedious manual QA process of a service oriented architecture. The tool uses Selenium to mimic user interactions in one app, and confirm that those interactions have the correct result in other apps within the system. Pusher notifies the tester immediately each time an automated check passes or fails.</p>
        </div>

